Provider: "How would you describe the pain? Sharp? Dull? Cramp-like? On a scale of 1 to 10?"
Patient: "It's a dull pain and it's probably about a 7."
Provider: "Is the pain traveling anywhere else on your body?"
Patient: "No. Just in my lower back."
Provider: "Are you having any pain when you pee?"
Patient: "Yes."
Provider: "Are you having to pee often? More often than normal?"
Patient: "Yes."
Provider: "Do you see any blood when you pee?"
Patient: "No, no blood."
Provider: "Are you feeling nauseous? Have you had to vomit?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Have you ever had kidney stones before?"
Patient: "No, not that I know of."
Provider: "Have you ever had a UTI before?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Do you take any medications?"
Patient: "I take Enalapril."
Provider: "Is that to treat your high blood pressure?"
Patient: "Yes, I think so."
Provider: "Do you know the dosage?"
Patient: "I think 30 mg."

Provider: "Hi Mr. James. Your doctor requested a urology consult to see if any interventions are needed with your kidney stone."
Patient: "Oh ok - hi."
Provider: "How is your pain? What would you rank it on a scale from 1 to 10?"
Patient: "I would say a 10 out of 10."
Provider: "I'm sorry, did you say 2 out of 10?"
Patient: "No, 10 not 2."
Provider: "Is the pain medication - ketorolac - helping?"
Patient: "A little bit."
Provider: "Got it. And that's on your right side?"
Patient: "Yes. My right lower back, but I feel it in my groin area too. And it's not all the time, but it comes in sharp bursts."
Provider: "Are you having any nausea or vomiting?"
Patient: "Yes, but it's gotten better."
Provider: "Are you having any pain when you pee?"
Patient: "Nope."
Provider: "Have you seen any blood in your pee?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "And I see in your chart that you had an obstructing kidney stone that required ureteroscopy about 2 years ago?"
Patient: "Yes, that's right."
Provider: "Ok. I'm going to do my exam now. Your abdomen is soft and non-distended. Can you please sit up? Is this pain full when I tap here?"
Patient: "It hurts a little bit."
Provider: "So mild right CVA tenderness. I'm also going to check your scrotum. I'm not seeing any swelling. Are you having any tenderness?"
Patient: "No, not at all."
Provider: "Based on my assessment, I do think we should proceed with ureteroscopy with laser lithotripsy and place a ureteral stent. We will be reviewing the risks with the procedure and will get your consent. Depending on how the procedure goes, we may need to stage them. After the procedure you may experience some pain when peeing and may feel urgency with the stent. I will plan to schedule the procedure for tomorrow morning. Do you have any questions?"
Patient: "No, that sounds good doc."

input:
Provider: "Good morning Mr. Sanchez. Your doctor requested urology evaluate you in case you had any BPH related obstruction."
Patient: "Ok - buenos dias."
Provider: "Can you tell me a little bit about what's going on?"
Patient: "I noticed my urine stream is not so strong anymore and I've been waking up to pee. Also sometimes it takes me a while to starting peeing. It's been getting worse over the last year, but this is the first time I haven't been able to pee at all."
Provider: "Are you having any pain?"
Patient: "When I first came in I had very bad pain low in my stomach, but whatever they did in the ED helped a lot."
Provider: "Have. you had any fevers or chills?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Any pain when you pee?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Have you noticed any blood in your urine recently?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "And I see here you have a history of BPH?"
Patient: "Si."
Provider: "But you've never had any surgery on your prostate?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Have you started any new medications recently?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "And you haven't had a stroke, or been diagnosed with Parkinson's or MS, or anything like that, correct?"
Patient: "No, no - nothing like that."
Provider: "Ok. I'm going to do my exam now. Your abdomen feels soft and is mildly distended. I'm not feeling any guarding. Any pain when I release pressure?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "I'm going to a quick exam of your genitals. I'm seeing normal external genitalia; no phimosis or meatal stenosis. Next I will need to check your prostate. Your prostate is smooth and symmetrically enlarged. Are you feeling any pain or tenderness?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Ok, so for now I think we should keep the Foley catheter in place at least for the next 2-3 days. We will then see how you do without the catheter. I also want to start you on a medication to help your BPH. It's called tamsulosin. I want you to take 0.4 mg by mouth once a day. I would like to see you again in my urology clinic in about 1-2 weeks. Do you have any questions?"
Patient: "No, doctor. That all sounds good. Gracias."
expected_outcome:
High Weightage:
1. History of present illness - Mr. Sanchez is a 72-year-old male [from chart} with a known history of BPH and presents with acute onset urinary retention. He reports a progressive decline in urinary stream strength, increased nocturia, and hesitancy over the past year, but never complete retention until now. He had significant suprapubic discomfort on arrival to the ED. ED team placed a Foley catheter with return of ~900 mL of clear yellow urine [from chart], leading to symptomatic relief. He denies fever, chills, dysuria, or hematuria. No prior prostate surgery. No new medications or neurological symptoms.
2. Physical exam - Abdomen - soft, mildly distended; no rebound or guarding; Genital exam- normal external genitalia; no phimosis or meatal stenosis; Rectal exam - smooth, symmetrically enlarged prostate, non-tender
3. Maintain Foley catheter in place - recommend catheter retention x2-3 days
4. Start medical therapy for BPH - initiate tamsulosin 0.4 mg PO daily
Medium Weightage:
5. Voiding trial - plan TWOC (trial without catheter) in 2-3 days
6. Follow-up - outpatient follow-up in urology clinic within 1-2 weeks post-TWOC
actual_output:
=== CLINICAL DATA EXTRACTION ===

1. Chief Complaint/Reason for Visit:
   - Patient reports a weak urine stream, difficulty initiating urination, and nocturia. These symptoms have been worsening over the past year, and the patient recently experienced acute urinary retention.

2. History of Present Illness (HPI):
   - Onset and duration: Symptoms have been worsening over the past year, with recent acute urinary retention.
   - Character/quality of symptoms: Weak urine stream, difficulty initiating urination, nocturia.
   - Severity: Severe enough to cause acute urinary retention.
   - Aggravating and alleviating factors: Alleviated by Foley catheter placement in the ED.
   - Associated symptoms: Lower abdominal pain, which was alleviated in the ED.
   - Previous episodes: No mention of previous episodes.

3. Current Medications: None mentioned.:

4. Allergies: None mentioned.:

5. Vital Signs: Not mentioned.:

6. Past Medical History:
   - Diagnosed with Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH).
   - No history of stroke, Parkinson's disease, or Multiple Sclerosis.

7. Surgical History: No history of prostate surgery.:

8. Family History: Not mentioned.:

9. Social History: Not mentioned.:

10. Review of Systems:
   - Denies fevers, chills, dysuria, and hematuria.

11. Physical Exam Findings:
   - Abdomen: Soft, mildly distended, no guarding, no pain on release of pressure.
   - Genitalia: Normal external genitalia, no phimosis or meatal stenosis.
   - Prostate: Smooth and symmetrically enlarged, no pain or tenderness.

12. Previous Test Results: Not mentioned.:

13. Assessment/Differential Diagnosis: BPH with acute urinary retention.:

14. Diagnostic Plan: Not mentioned.:

15. Treatment Plan:
   - Medications prescribed/changed: Tamsulosin 0.4 mg orally once daily for BPH.
   - Non-pharmacological interventions: Foley catheter to remain in place for 2-3 days.
   - Follow-up: Urology clinic in 1-2 weeks.

16. Patient Education: Explained the need for Foley catheter and the use of tamsulosin for BPH.:

Provider: "Hello Ms. Jacobson. Can you tell me what brings you in today?"
Patient: "I've been throwing up and feeling weak for the past few days."
Provider: "OK. I see here that you have type 2 diabetes?"
Patient: "Well I was told I have high sugar."
Provider: "Are you having any pain?"
Patient: "My stomach doesn't feel good, but I'm not having any pain really."
Provider: "Are you feeling thirsty? And peeing more than usual?"
Patient: "Yes. And I'm not really feeling hungry and haven't been eating much."
Provider: "Have you been checking your blood glucose?"
Patient: "Yeah, my sugar has been high."
Provider: "Do you remember what it's been?"
Patient: "Like 400 and 500. I mean I know it's been higher than it should be. I might have forgotten to take my insulin a little bit here and there. I just kinda forgot."
Provider: "I see. Have you ever come to the hospital before for your diabetes, or for having these same symptoms?"
Patient: "No. This is the first time."
Provider: "Are you having any chest pain or shortness of breath?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Have you traveled recently?"
Patient: "No. Not since last year."
Provider: "Has anyone you know been sick?"
Patient: "No, not that I know of."
Provider: "Have you had a fever?"
Patient: "I haven't had a temperature."
expected_outcome:
High Weightage:
1. Chief complaint: "I've been throwing up and feeling weak for the past few days."
2. History of present illness: Ms. Jacobson is a 35-year-old female [chart] with known type 2 diabetes mellitus, presenting with nausea, vomiting, generalized weakness, and abdominal discomfort for the past 2-3 days. The patient also reports increased thirst, frequent urination, and poor oral intake. Blood glucose at home was noted to be in the 400-500s. The patient reports missing several doses of insulin due to noncompliance. No history of DKA episodes. Denies chest pain, shortness of breath, or recent travel. No known sick contacts. Denies fever.
actual_output:
=== CLINICAL DATA EXTRACTION ===

1. Chief Complaint/Reason for Visit:
   - Patient reports vomiting and feeling weak for the past few days

2. History of Present Illness (HPI):
   - Onset and duration: Symptoms started a few days ago
   - Character/quality of symptoms: Patient has been vomiting and feeling weak
   - Associated symptoms: Patient reports increased thirst, increased urination, lack of appetite, and stomach discomfort
   - Previous episodes: This is the first time the patient has experienced these symptoms

3. Current Medications:
   - Patient is on insulin for diabetes, but admits to occasional non-compliance

4. Past Medical History:
   - Patient has a known history of type 2 diabetes

5. Review of Systems:
   - Patient denies chest pain, shortness of breath, and fever
   - Patient has not been eating much due to lack of appetite

6. Assessment/Differential Diagnosis:
   - The provider is considering poor glycemic control due to the patient's high blood glucose readings and symptoms of increased thirst, urination, and vomiting

7. Patient Education:
   - The provider has asked the patient about her symptoms and blood glucose levels to educate her about the importance of regular insulin use and monitoring of blood glucose levels

=== END OF EXTRACTION ===

Provider: "Tell me a little more about your cough."

Provider: "I see. Any blood?"
Patient: "No, no blood."
Provider: "Have you had a fever? Chills?"
Patient: "Yes. I've had a fever and have gotten the chills."
Provider: "Is there anyone you've been in contact with that has been sick?"
Patient: "Not that I know of."
Provider: "Any recent travel?"
Patient: "Nope."
Provider: "Any pain in your chest? Especially when you breath, laugh, or cough?"
Patient: "Definitely."
Provider: "Are you having shortness of breath?"
Patient: "Yes, it feels like I can't catch my breath."
Provider: "Have you been eating normally? Any nausea? Vomiting?"
Patient: "I haven't been as hungry as usual, but I'm not really feeling nauseous and not vomiting."
Provider: "Have you had any diarrhea?"
Patient: "No."
Provider: "Ok. I'm going to start my exam now. First let me listen to your lungs. Do you smoke or vape?"
Patient: "I used to smoke, but I stopped about 5 years ago."
Provider: "Oh, ok. How much did you smoke?"
Patient: "About a pack a day."
Provider: "And for how long? How many years?"
Patient: "About 20 years."
Provider: "Ok. I'm hearing decreased breath sounds with crackles in your right left lobe. Can you please say the letter "eee" sound for me?"
Patient: "Eee, eee, eee, eee"
Provider: "Perfect, thank you. I am hearing egophony. And I see you are having to work a bit harder to breathe."
